fields.title: Behind the Scenes of Hitting “Enter” on www.google.com: A Closer Look. PART ONE
fields.title_tag: Behind the Scenes of Hitting “Enter” on www.google.com: A Closer Look. PART ONE
fields.body: Picture this: you’ve just decided to visit one of the most renowned websites on the internet, the almighty Google. You open your web browser, eagerly type in “https://www.google.com," and press Enter. What unfolds from here is nothing short of an epic digital journey, and we’re here to embark on it together through this three-part blog series. In this first part, we’ll take an in-depth look at the initial stages of your online adventure, including the DNS request and the establishment of a TCP/IP connection. The DNS Request: As you hit that Enter key, your web browser faces its first task: it needs to figure out where in the vast expanse of the internet “www.google.com" is located. Initially, it has no clue. To resolve this mystery, your browser takes a cue from a global network of servers known as the Domain Name System (DNS). Think of DNS as the internet’s equivalent of a meticulously organized phonebook. Your browser promptly sends a request to a DNS server, which holds the answers. It’s akin to asking for the exact location of “www.google.com." The DNS server promptly responds with the IP address linked to this web address. Now, your browser knows precisely where to go, much like finding a specific address on a map. TCP/IP — Knocking on the Server’s Door: Armed with this newfound knowledge, your web browser proceeds to communicate with Google’s servers. It does so using a set of protocols collectively known as TCP/IP (Transmission Control Protocol/Internet Protocol). These protocols serve as the guiding principles that underpin how data is exchanged across the vast expanse of the internet. Establishing a TCP/IP connection with Google’s server is the same as knocking on the server’s virtual door and saying, “I’d like to have a conversation with you.” This connection is essential for the smooth exchange of information between your browser and the server. It operates on a specific port, commonly port 443 for HTTPS. We’ll delve further into the significance of this in the upcoming second part of our journey. So, keep those digital bags packed and get ready to explore the intricacies of data security as our enthralling digital journey unfolds before us! PART TWO Beyond the Firewall — SSL, Load-Balancer, and Web Server
